  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.731957Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-687-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The square root operation is equivalent to the exponent 0.5 where the base is the term under the square root."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733527Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-687-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "You can deduce this as squaring and square rooting are inverse operations."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733531Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-687-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Since the exponents for each term are the same, they can be combined."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733534Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8207-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The distributive law can be used with expressions containing surds."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733538Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8207-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "This can be extended to finding the product of two or more binomials."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733542Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8207-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Any binomial could contain surd terms."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733546Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-486-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is possible to find a solution that satisfies a problem with two unknowns by trial and error."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733750Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-486-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """It is possible to use the difference between the two scenarios to create a third valid scenario."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733754Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-486-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Once you know one of the unknowns, you can substitute to find the other."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733758Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-783-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A logical argument is a series of statements that progress in a clear way."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733762Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-783-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Each subsequent statement is based on the previous statement being true."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733766Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-783-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "If a contradiction is reached, it shows that the original assumption was wrong."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733771Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-505-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Both the LCM and HCF can be found by comparing the prime factorisation of the numbers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733776Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-505-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A Venn diagram can be a helpful representation."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733780Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-505-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "This representation can be extended to consider three numbers."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733784Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-505-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The context of the question can make it clear whether the LCM or HCF would be the most useful."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733788Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-467-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The distributive law can be used to find the two factors of a quadratic expression with three non-zero terms."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733791Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-467-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "An area model can be used to explore the underlying structure."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733795Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-467-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """You can check your factors by finding the product and checking it against the quadratic."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733799Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-464-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Rearranging the formula may be beneficial when what you wish to calculate is not the subject."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733803Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-464-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "You can compare rearranging the formula to solving for one unknown."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733807Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-464-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Instead of finding a value though, you will find an expression that the variable is equal to."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.733811Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-513-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """When adding numbers represented in standard form, place value is an important consideration."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.734574Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-513-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "If the power of 10 is the same for both numbers, it is easy to add."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.734578Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-513-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Standard form calculations can be done using a calculator."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.734582Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-852-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There is a shorthand for writing a function"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.734845Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-852-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The notation means that the whole function does not need to be written out each time"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.734848Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-852-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The notation should always be defined at the start"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.734852Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-852-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "It is possible to substitute the notation for the function it represents"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.734856Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-493-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Repeated percentage change occurs in real-life."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.735450Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-493-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Simple interest is calculated once and then added repeatedly."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.735453Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-493-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Compound interest is recalculated at each stage."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.735457Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-493-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By considering the calculations for compound interest, you can be more efficient."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.735461Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-493-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Calculators can simplify this process even further."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.735465Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-481-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """You can use your knowledge of changing the subject to rewrite one or both equations."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.736151Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-481-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If one of the variables is the subject, the equivalent expression can be substituted into the other equation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.736154Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-481-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "This is another method that involves reducing the number of variables."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.736160Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-789-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The term-to-term rule is the common difference."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.736932Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-789-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Finding the common difference can help when finding the n^th  term rule."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.736936Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-789-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Comparing the sequence to an appropriate multiplication table can help identify the translation that has been made."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.736942Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-789-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The n^th term can be found for all arithmetic sequences."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.736948Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-695-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Before performing any operation, equivalent fractions should be considered."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.736952Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-695-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Algebraic fractions follow the same rules as fractions."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.736956Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-695-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "It is important to maintain equivalence between two algebraic statements."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.736960Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-695-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Multiplying both connected statements by the reciprocal can simplify."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.736964Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-685-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The radicand should be as small as possible."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.736968Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-685-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If any of the radicand's factors are square numbers then the surd can be simplified."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.736971Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-685-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Algebraic factors that are square values also mean the surd can be simplified."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.736975Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-475-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Quadratic equations can model real-life situations."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.737065Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-475-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Solutions would need to be interpreted in context."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.737068Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-475-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The difference of two squares is not only used in algebra, but can be used to quickly calculate numerical expressions."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.737072Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-474-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The quadratic formula can be derived from the general form of a quadratic equation."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.738017Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-474-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "It can be derived by completing the square."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.738021Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-474-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The formula is useful when the quadratic cannot be easily factorised."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.738027Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-474-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Technology can be used to identify solutions and is useful for checking."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.738031Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7227-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The base could be a number, letter or combination of the two."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.738190Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7227-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The laws are another way you can simplify an expression."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.738194Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-7227-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Plotting numbers against their squared values can help you estimate unknown amounts."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.738198Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-688-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The multiplication of surds can be generalised."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.738202Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-688-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "√a × √b=√ab  and √a × √(1/b) = √(a/b) = √a ÷ √b"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.738206Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-688-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "You may be able to simplify this product."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.738209Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8187-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Numbers can be classified as surds or not surds."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.739057Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8187-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Square factors of numerical and algebraic terms can be identified."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.739063Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-8187-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The highest square term is the one needed when simplifying surds."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.739067Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-489-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Percentages can be written as a fraction out of 100"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.739481Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-489-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "One number can be written as a fraction of another."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.739485Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-489-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Representations can support the finding a percentage of a quantity."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.739489Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-489-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A percentage can be written as a decimal called a multiplier."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.739493Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-489-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "This multiplier can be used to find a percentage of an amount."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.739497Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-772-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A function has a set of inputs and outputs."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.739501Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-772-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "For any valid input, there is an output."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.739505Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-772-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A function takes an input and performs a series of operations, leading to an output."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.739509Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-772-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The set of inputs is called the domain."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.739513Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-772-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The set of outputs is called the range."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.739517Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-460-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The term could have any form such as fractional or algebraic and may contain exponents."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740806Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-460-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The expression may be comprised of multiple terms."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740810Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-460-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If either the term or expression are identical to another term or expression, these can be combined."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740814Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-459-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A single number or letter, or the product of numbers and/or variables."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740826Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-459-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An expression contains one or more terms, where each term is separated by an operator."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740831Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-459-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "An equation is a statement that two expressions are equal, indicated by ="@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740835Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-459-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """An identity is an equation which is always true, regardless of the values substituted in."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740839Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-459-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """A formula is a mathematical rule or relationship connecting two or more variables."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740845Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-645-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The sum of the exterior angles of a polygon can be demonstrated using a point."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740850Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-645-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The sum of the exterior angles of a polygon can be proven using interior angles and the angles on a straight line."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740854Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-645-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "An exterior and interior angles pair are supplementary."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740858Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-795-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Identifying a common ratio between each term can help us identify a geometric sequence."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740861Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-795-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Divide each term by its previous consecutive term, if the results are all the same, this is the common ratio."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740865Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-795-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "If there is a common ratio, then the sequence is geometric."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.740869Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-788-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
