  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A vector's magnitude can be calculated."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.746568Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-841-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "This is the same as calculating the length of a line."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.746575Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-841-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Pythagoras' theorem can be used."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.746579Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-776-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A function may have a given output."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747294Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-776-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "It is possible to solve to find the input."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747298Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-564-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Histograms can be drawn quickly using technology"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747302Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-564-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Using the raw data allows software to calculate equal bin widths easily"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747306Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-564-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Box plots can be drawn using the same data to allow comparison"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747310Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-564-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "You can compare the shape of the histogram to its box plot"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747316Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-801-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """Iterative formulae use the previous iteration's output for this iteration's input"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747320Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-801-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A population can be estimated using an iterative formula"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747324Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-801-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Efficient use of the calculator makes this process much faster"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.747328Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-506-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Integer indices state how often a number should be multiplied by itself."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.748615Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-506-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The square root of any perfect square  will be an integer."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.748621Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-506-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The square root of any number can be found using a calculator but it may not be an integer."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.748625Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-506-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The square root of any number can be estimated by comparing the square roots of the closest perfect squares."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.748629Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-684-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "There is always a choice regarding how you represent a value."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.748635Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-684-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "You need to consider the most suitable way for the situation."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.748639Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-684-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Rounding reduces accuracy so a rounded answer is not always useful."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.748643Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-684-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """There are agreed forms: one operation remaining and the result of the operation would produce a non-terminating decimal."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.748647Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-684-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Surd form is one such acceptable way."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.748651Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-507-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "When multiplying two terms, you can sometimes write this more simply."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749418Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-507-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If the powers have the same base, then the powers can be combined into a single power."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749422Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-507-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "The exponent or index of the new power reflects this combination."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749426Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-507-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """By studying the structure of multiplication, you can see how the index will change."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749430Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-507-5
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "a^b × a^c = a^(b+c)"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749434Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-792-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The n^th term rule can calculate the position of the value that is equal to the given value."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749438Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-792-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "If this is not an integer, then you can round down or up as needed."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749441Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-792-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "This term number can be used to generate the desired value."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749460Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-490-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """In all of these representations a single multiplier can be used to find a percentage increase."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749467Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-490-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Representation can help when you are not using a calculator."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749472Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-490-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "A multiplier is significantly faster when using a calculator."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749476Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-490-4
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "To increase, you are going above the original amount."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.749482Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-853-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label "Changing the function changes what it represents"@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.750025Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-853-2
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """The change in notation can be seen in the algebraic form of the function it represents"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.750029Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-853-3
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
  rdfs:label """If a specific linear function is considered, the effects of this can be seen clearly"""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-02-12T08:59:21.750033Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:keylearningpoint-lesson-787-1
  a curric:KeyLearningPoint ;
